## Future of Interaction? Richer and Everywhere
[Chris Harrison](http://www.chrisharrison.net/projects/omnitouch/omnitouch.pdf) (CMU HCII)

The iPhone 6 is as powerful as the CM-5 was in 1994. In that time, computing factors have increased in power, but human factors have stayed exactly the same. The current industry answer is to link screen size to capability (enormous phablets, useless smartwatches).

Hands have a huge number of capabilities, but touch devices only take advantage of various pokes. Long story short: touch is awesome, but now we need to make it better.

Examples:
- [TapSense: Enhancing Finger Interaction on Touch Surfaces](http://www.chrisharrison.net/index.php/Research/TapSense)
- [PointPose: Finger Pose Estimation For Touch Input On Mobile Devices Using A Depth Sensor](http://dl.acm.org/citation.cfm?id=2512824)
- [TouchTools: Leveraging Familiarity and Skill with Physical Tools to Augment Touch Interaction](http://www.chrisharrison.net/index.php/Research/Touchtools)

We also need to escape the small confines of mobile devices to take touch everywhere. Today, computing happens in little rectangles, but what we really want is to explode computing out into the world.

Examples:
- [OmniTouch: Wearable Multitouch Interaction Everywhere](http://www.chrisharrison.net/projects/omnitouch/omnitouch.pdf)
- [WorldKit: Rapid And Easy Creation Of Ad-hoc Interactive Applications On Everyday Surfaces](http://dl.acm.org/citation.cfm?id=2466113)
